LAGOS – Senator Kashamu Buruji, the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) governorship candidate in Ogun State, has promised to provide good welfare packages and stomach infrastructure for people of the state, if elected. Buruji disclosed this on Tuesday during a visit to the religious and traditions leaders in Ado-Odo Ota Local Government Area of the state. Some of the leaders he visited included the Olota-in-Council, the Council of Baales and Chiefs, the League of Imams and Alfas, the Christian Association of Nigeria (CAN), the Hausa community, the Igbo community, traditionalists, artisans and market men and women The Olota of Ota, Oba Adeyemi Abdulkabir Obalanlege (Ekun II), led other traditional rulers in Aworiland to receive the governorship candidate. Speaking at the various fora, Kashamu said the welfare of the people would be his priority, if elected. “I commit to completing all the uncompleted and ongoing projects in Ogun-West Senatorial District and other parts of the state. Our government will be tax-friendly and encourage more businesses to thrive. “I reckon that our people are in need of basic infrastructure, such as potable water, good and motorable roads in most parts of the state. All of these and many more will be done if you vote PDP on Saturday and March 9,” Kashamu said. He highlighted some of his policies if elected as governor, adding, “One, I commit to releasing all allocations due to local governments. I will not deduct from their allocations. This is to ensure grassroots development and allow the traditional institution to be involved in local government administration.” “Two, I also commit to remitting all statutory deductions from staff salaries to the relevant unions and authorities as and when due.” He promised that all the money deducted from civil servants for cooperatives which have not been paid would be paid. “We will meet with the leaders and do whatever they want. Their backlog of co-operative money for 106 months would be paid.”